l", "Erin T. Mansur", "Celeste Saravia"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050207_app.zip", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "237-66", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050207_app.zip", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Vertical Arrangements, Market Structure, and Competition: An Analysis of Restructured US Electricity Markets", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "This paper examines vertical arrangements in electricity markets. Vertically"}, {"e:author": ["Daron Acemoglu", "James A. Robinson"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.267", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "267-93", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.267", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Persistence of Power, Elites, and Institutions", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "We construct a model to study the implications of changes in political institutions"}, {"e:author": ["Iris Bohnet", "Fiona Greig", "Benedikt Herrmann", "Richard Zeckhauser"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20051024_app.pdf", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "294-310", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20051024_app.pdf", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Betrayal Aversion: Evidence from Brazil, China, Oman, Switzerland, Turkey, and the United States", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "Due to betrayal aversion, people take risks less willingly when the agent of"}, {"e:author": ["Ebonya L. Washington"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050902_data.zip", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "311-32", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050902_data.zip", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Female Socialization: How Daughters Affect Their Legislator Fathers", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "Parenting daughters, sociologists have shown, increases feminist sympathies."}, {"e:author": ["Eric D. Gould", "Omer Moav", "Avi Simhon"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.333", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "333-57", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.333", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "The Mystery of Monogamy", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "We examine why developed societies are monogamous while rich men throughout"}, {"e:author": ["Ricardo J. Caballero", "Emmanuel Farhi", "Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20060199_data.zip", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "358-93", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20060199_data.zip", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "An Equilibrium Model of &quot;Global Imbalances&quot; and Low Interest Rates", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "The sustained rise in US current account deficits, the stubborn decline in long-run"}, {"e:author": ["Lucia Foster", "John Haltiwanger", "Chad Syverson"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050803_app.pdf", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "394-425", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050803_app.pdf", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Reallocation, Firm Turnover, and Efficiency: Selection on Productivity or Profitability?", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "We investigate the nature of selection and productivity growth in industries"}, {"e:author": ["Paolo Angelini", "Andrea Generale"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050397_app.pdf", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "426-38", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050397_app.pdf", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "On the Evolution of Firm Size Distributions", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "We study the impact of financial constraints on firm size distribution (FSD). We find that financially constrained firms, identified using various proxies, are smaller than the others (their FSD is more skewed to the right). However, among OECD countries, the FSD of nonconstrained firms virtually overlaps  that of the entire sample, suggesting that the overall impact of financial constraints on the FSD is modest. The difference is more pronounced in our sample of firms from non-OECD countries. We conclude that financial constraints cannot be considered the main determinant of the FSD evolution in developed economies. (JEL L11, L25)"}, {"e:author": ["Valerie Cerra", "Sweta Chaman Saxena"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050666_data.zip", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "439-57", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050666_data.zip", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Growth Dynamics: The Myth of Economic Recovery", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "Using panel data for a large set of high-income, emerging market, developing, and transition countries, we find robust evidence that the large output loss from financial crises and some types of political crises is highly persistent. The results on financial crises are also highly robust to the assumption on exogeneity. Moreover, we find strong evidence of growth over optimism before financial crises. We also find a distinction between the output impact of civil wars versus other crises, in that there is a partial output rebound for civil wars but no significant rebound for financial crises or the other political crises. (JEL  D72, D74, E32, E44, O17, O47)"}, {"e:author": ["Jonathan Guryan", "Melissa S. Kearney"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050694_data.zip", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "458-73", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20050694_data.zip", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Gambling at Lucky Stores: Empirical Evidence from State Lottery Sales", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "We show that the week after selling a large-prize Texas Lotto winning ticket, a retailer experiences a 12 to 38 percent relative increase in ticket sales. Some increase persists for up to 40 weeks. We document that the sales response increases with jackpot size and is larger in areas with more economically disadvantaged populations. Sales patterns across games and across retailers are not consistent with most advertising explanations. Furthermore, response patterns are not consistent with representativeness-based explanations for the hot hand or gambler's fallacy; we suggest an alternative explanation for the observed \"lucky store\" effect. (JEL H27, H71)"}, {"e:author": ["Marjorie Flavin", "Shinobu Nakagawa"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20031145_data.zip", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "474-95", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20031145_data.zip", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "A Model of Housing in the Presence of Adjustment Costs: A Structural Interpretation of Habit Persistence", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "The paper provides a model of household consumption and portfolio allocation which incorporates housing as both a consumption good and a component of wealth. Household utility depends, possibly nonseparably, on two goods: nondurable consumption, which is costlessly adjustable, and housing, which is subject to a nonconvex adjustment cost. Households face"}, {"e:author": ["Juan-Pablo Montero"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.496", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "496-518", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.496", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "A Simple Auction Mechanism for the Optimal Allocation of the Commons", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "Efficient regulation of the commons requires information about the regulated firms that is rarely available to regulators (e.g., cost of pollution abatement). This paper proposes a simple mechanism that implements the first-best for any number of firms: a uniform price, sealed-bid auction of an endogenous number of  (transferable) licenses with a fraction of the auction revenues given back to firms. Paybacks, which rapidly decrease with the number of firms, are such that truth-telling is a dominant strategy regardless of whether firms behave non-cooperatively or collusively. The mechanism also provides firms with incentives to invest in socially optimal R&D. (JEL D44, L51, Q21)"}, {"e:author": ["J&oacute;n Steinsson"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20070484_data.zip", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "519-33", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar08/20070484_data.zip", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "The Dynamic Behavior of the Real Exchange Rate in Sticky Price Models", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "Existing empirical evidence suggests that real exchange rates exhibit hump-shaped dynamics. I show that this is a robust fact across nine large, developed economies. This fact can help explain why sticky price business cycle models have been unable to match the persistence of the real exchange rate. I show that, in response to a number of different real shocks, a two-country sticky price business cycle model yields hump-shaped dynamics for the real exchange rate. The hump-shaped dynamics generated by the model are a powerful source of endogenous persistence that allows the model to match the long half-life of the real exchange rate. (JEL F31)"}, {"e:author": ["Roberta Dess&iacute;"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.534", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "534-60", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.534", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Collective Memory, Cultural Transmission, and Investments", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "I study the transmission of collective memory as a mechanism for cultural transmission, in the presence of social externalities associated with individual cultural investment decisions. The younger generation's decisions depend on beliefs about the quality of existing institutions, norms, and values, which are influenced by collective memory. In culturally homogeneous societies it can be optimal to suppress negative memories while emphasizing positive ones. However, the ability to bias collective memory is costly: it may generate cultural overoptimism and overinvestment in some cases, the reverse in other cases. The scope for welfare-enhancing manipulation of collective memory is reduced, moreover, in culturally heterogeneous societies. (JEL D83, Z13)"}, {"e:author": ["Fuhito Kojima"], "e:volume": "98", "e:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.561", "e:keyword": [], "e:pages": "561-62", "e:issn": "0002-8282", "e:issue": "1", "e:doi": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.98.1.561", "e:year": 2008, "e:title": "Bureaucrats or Politicians? Comment", "e:journal": "American Economic Review", "e:abstract": "Alesina and Tabellini (2007) investigate the normative criteria for allocating policy tasks to bureaucrats versus politicians. While they establish criteria with respect to a number of parameters, they do not give a criterion with respect to the degree of imperfect monitoring. We establish an unambiguous criterion about imperfect monitoring. (JEL  D72, D73)"}]